Trypanosomiasis - Uganda 19980508.0899
Date: Mon, 29 Oct 2001
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@vet.gla.ac.uk>
Source Africa News Service 26 October 2001 [edited

Rwanda: Sleeping sickness
--------------------------------------
A total of 25 people Bulongo and Butansi, Luuka county, Iganga
district, have been confirmed to be suffering from sleeping sickness,
reports Moses Nampala. A medical clinical officer, James Zironda, said
several cases handled by his unit had sleeping sickness, a disease
caused by the bite of a tsetse fly. "The biggest percentage of the
patients we are handling have fresh irritations that developed as a
result of recent bites from tsetse flies," Zironda said.
He attributed the re-emergence of sleeping sickness to the presence of
a vast thicket of Lantana Camara, a wild plant that harbours the
tsetse flies. Local Council officials in Rwanda village, Bulongo
county blamed the re-emergence of the disease to delays by vector
control authorities in administering preventive measures. "The last
time we had an aerial spray was 6 years ago," Ibrahim Kyoka, a
resident, said.
Residents said tsetse fly traps provided 6 years ago needed to be
replaced. Zironda regretted that some sleeping sickness victims
avoided medical treatment and sought help from native herbalists,
mistaking the disease for lunacy. As a result, some patients
reportedly died.
